of themajor novelists of the long eighteenth century - Defoe, Fielding, Smollett, Sterne and Austen - Chris Ewers shows how these two developments interacted. He argues that this reconfiguration of local geography and the new experience of moving through space at speed had a profound effect upon the narrative and form of the novel, leaving its mark on genre, prose technique, the depiction of class and gender relations and the way texts are structured. It is noaccident, he concludes, that the arrival of the novel, the literary form that uses life-as-a-journey as a master trope, is roughly co-terminous with the revolution of internal transport in Britain. CHRIS EWERS is a lecturer in Eighteenth Century Literature at the University of Exeter  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish fictiony18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aTransportation in literature. 0aTransportationxSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh  aEnglish novel.  aeighteenth-century literature.  aliterary analysis.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary evolution.  aliterary exploration.  aliterary impact.  aliterary influence.  aliterary interpretation.  aliterary perspective.  aliterary study.  aliterary themes.  anarrative structure.  anovel development.  anovel form.  asocial mobility.  atransport revolution.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311143106240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787442726?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787442726423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787442726/original  a978-3-11-143106-2  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles